In this example, we will create a simple Employee class, configure Hibernate and H2 database, and persist an Employee object to the H2 database using Hibernate.

1. First, add the necessary dependencies to your project. In case you are using Maven, add the following dependencies to your pom.xml:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.hibernate</groupId>
        <artifactId>hibernate-core</artifactId>
        <version>5.4.32.Final</version>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>
        <artifactId>h2</artifactId>
        <version>1.4.200</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

2. Create the Employee class and annotate it with the necessary JPA annotations:

```java
import javax.persistence.Entity;
import javax.persistence.GeneratedValue;
import javax.persistence.GenerationType;
import javax.persistence.Id;

@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String position;

    // constructors, getters, and setters
}
```

3. Create a Hibernate configuration file (hibernate.cfg.xml) inside your project's resources folder:

```xml
<!DOCTYPE hibernate-configuration PUBLIC
        "-//Hibernate/Hibernate Configuration DTD 3.0//EN"
        "http://www.hibernate.org/dtd/hibernate-configuration-3.0.dtd">
<hibernate-configuration>
    <session-factory>
        <!-- Database connection settings -->
        <property name="connection.driver_class">org.h2.Driver</property>
        <property name="connection.url">jdbc:h2:~/test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1;AUTO_SERVER=TRUE</property>
        <property name="connection.username">sa</property>
        <property name="connection.password"></property>

        <!-- JDBC connection pool -->
        <property name="connection.pool_size">5</property>

        <!-- SQL dialect -->
        <property name="dialect">org.hibernate.dialect.H2Dialect</property>

        <!-- Enable Hibernate's automatic session context management -->
        <property name="current_session_context_class">thread</property>

        <!-- Disable the second-level cache -->
        <property name="cache.provider_class">org.hibernate.cache.internal.NoCacheProvider</property>

        <!-- Echo all executed SQL to stdout -->
        <property name="show_sql">true</property>

        <!-- Drop and re-create the database schema on startup -->
        <property name="hbm2ddl.auto">update</property>

        <!-- Register the Employee class -->
        <mapping class="your.package.name.Employee"/>
    </-session-factory>
</hibernate-configuration>
```

4. Create a utility class to get the Hibernate session factory:

```java
import org.hibernate.SessionFactory;
import org.hibernate.boot.Metadata;
import org.hibernate.boot.MetadataSources;
import org.hibernate.boot.registry.StandardServiceRegistry;
import org.hibernate.boot.registry.StandardServiceRegistryBuilder;

public class HibernateUtil {

    private static final SessionFactory sessionFactory;

    static {
        try {
            StandardServiceRegistry standardRegistry = new StandardServiceRegistryBuilder()
                    .configure("hibernate.cfg.xml")
                    .build();
            Metadata metadata = new MetadataSources(standardRegistry).getMetadataBuilder().build();
            sessionFactory = metadata.getSessionFactoryBuilder().build();
        } catch (Throwable ex) {
            System.err.println("Initial SessionFactory creation failed." + ex);
            throw new ExceptionInInitializerError(ex);
        }
    }

    public static SessionFactory getSessionFactory() {
        return sessionFactory;
    }
}
```

5. Now, you can create a new employee object and persist it to the H2 database using Hibernate:

```java
import org.hibernate.Session;
import org.hibernate.Transaction;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee employee = new Employee();
        employee.setName("John Doe");
        employee.setPosition("Software Engineer");

        Transaction transaction = null;
        try (Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession()) {
            // Start a transaction
            transaction = session.beginTransaction();

            // Persist the Employee object
            session.save(employee);

            // Commit transaction
            transaction.commit();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            if (transaction != null) {
                transaction.rollback();
            }
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

Running the "Main" class should persist the new employee object to the H2 database.

Please note that this is just an example of using H2 and Hibernate to persist an Employee object. In a production environment, you should consider using a more sophisticated architecture and error handling.

In the following example, we will add error handling to our Hibernate code using exception handling and logging. First, you need to add a logging framework to your project. Assuming you are using Maven, add the following dependencies to your `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <!-- Your existing dependencies -->

    <!-- SLF4J logging -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.slf4j</groupId>
        <artifactId>slf4j-api</artifactId>
        <version>1.7.32</version>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.slf4j</groupId>
        <artifactId>slf4j-simple</artifactId>
        <version>1.7.32</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

Next, create a new class called `EmployeeDao` to handle Employee-related database operations, including error handling:

```java
import org.hibernate.Session;
import org.hibernate.Transaction;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class EmployeeDao {

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(EmployeeDao.class);

    public Long save(Employee employee) {
        Transaction transaction = null;
        Long employeeId = null;
        try (Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession()) {
            transaction = session.beginTransaction();
            employeeId = (Long) session.save(employee);
            transaction.commit();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            if (transaction != null) {
                transaction.rollback();
            }
            logger.error("Error saving employee", e);
        }

        return employeeId;
    }
}
```

Finally, modify the `Main` class to use the new `EmployeeDao` class to save an employee:

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee employee = new Employee();
        employee.setName("John Doe");
        employee.setPosition("Software Engineer");

        EmployeeDao employeeDao = new EmployeeDao();
        Long employeeId = employeeDao.save(employee);

        if (employeeId != null) {
            System.out.println("Employee saved with ID: " + employeeId);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Error saving employee.");
        }
    }
}
```

Now, if there's an exception while saving an employee, it will be logged using the SLF4J logging framework and the `save` method will return `null`. The `Main` class checks the return value and prints an appropriate message.

It's worth noting that the error handling in this example deals with generic exceptions. In a real-world application, you should consider handling more specific exceptions (e.g., `ConstraintViolationException` for unique constraint violations) to provide more detailed error messages and recovery options.

To demonstrate handling a `ConstraintViolationException` for a unique constraint violation, we'll first update the `Employee` class to set a unique constraint on the `email` field. Additionally, we'll include this field in our example:

1. Update the `Employee` class to add a unique constraint on the `email` field:

```java
import javax.persistence.Column;
import javax.persistence.Entity;
import javax.persistence.GeneratedValue;
import javax.persistence.GenerationType;
import javax.persistence.Id;
import javax.persistence.Table;

@Entity
@Table(name = "employee")
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String position;

    @Column(unique = true)
    private String email;

    // constructors, getters, and setters
}
```

2. Update the `EmployeeDao` class to handle `ConstraintViolationException` for unique constraint violations:

```java
import org.hibernate.Session;
import org.hibernate.Transaction;
import org.hibernate.exception.ConstraintViolationException;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class EmployeeDao {

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(EmployeeDao.class);

    public Long save(Employee employee) {
        Transaction transaction = null;
        Long employeeId = null;
        try (Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession()) {
            transaction = session.beginTransaction();
            employeeId = (Long) session.save(employee);
            transaction.commit();
        } catch (ConstraintViolationException e) {
            if (transaction != null) {
                transaction.rollback();
            }
            logger.error("Unique constraint violation on email: {}", employee.getEmail(), e);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            if (transaction != null) {
                transaction.rollback();
            }
            logger.error("Error saving employee", e);
        }

        return employeeId;
    }
}
```

3. Modify the `Main` class to set the `email` field and handle unique constraint violations:

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee employee = new Employee();
        employee.setName("John Doe");
        employee.setPosition("Software Engineer");
        employee.setEmail("john.doe@example.com");

        EmployeeDao employeeDao = new EmployeeDao();
        Long employeeId = employeeDao.save(employee);

        if (employeeId != null) {
            System.out.println("Employee saved with ID: " + employeeId);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Error saving employee. Email might not be unique.");
        }
    }
}
```

Now, if an attempt is made to save a new employee with the same email address as an existing employee, the `ConstraintViolationException` will be caught, and an appropriate log message will be printed. The `Main` class will also display an error message, which may indicate that the email address is not unique. In a real-world application, you may want to inform the user with a more detailed message and prompt them to re-enter the email address.

A full implementation of a drag-and-drop Swing GUI editor is a complex project. However, I can provide you with an example of how you can create a simple Swing application that allows you to drag and drop 10 example components at runtime.

1. First, let's create a class `DraggablePanel` which extends `JPanel` to represent draggable Swing components:

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.MouseAdapter;
import java.awt.event.MouseEvent;

public class DraggablePanel extends JPanel {

    private Point initialClick;

    public DraggablePanel() {
        addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
            public void mousePressed(MouseEvent e) {
                initialClick = e.getPoint();
            }
        });

        addMouseMotionListener(new MouseAdapter() {
            public void mouseDragged(MouseEvent e) {
                int deltaX = e.getX() - initialClick.x;
                int deltaY = e.getY() - initialClick.y;

                setLocation(getX() + deltaX, getY() + deltaY);
            }
        });
    }
}
```

2. Next, create a `ComponentFactory` class to create different types of components:

```java
import javax.swing.*;

public class ComponentFactory {

    public static DraggablePanel createSampleComponent(String type) {
        DraggablePanel panel = new DraggablePanel();
        switch (type) {
            case "Button":
                JButton button = new JButton("Button");
                panel.add(button);
                break;
            case "Label":
                JLabel label = new JLabel("Label");
                panel.add(label);
                break;
            // Add additional cases for more components
        }
        panel.setBorder(BorderFactory.createLineBorder(Color.BLACK, 2));
        panel.setSize(panel.getPreferredSize());
        return panel;
    }
}
```

3. Create the main Swing application with a `JPanel` that accepts dropped components, and a `JList` that allows users to drag and drop components into the panel:

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.datatransfer.DataFlavor;
import java.awt.datatransfer.Transferable;
import java.awt.dnd.DnDConstants;
import java.awt.dnd.DropTarget;
import java.awt.dnd.DropTargetAdapter;
import java.awt.dnd.DropTargetDropEvent;

public class DragAndDropGUI {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame mainFrame = new JFrame("Drag and Drop Components");
        mainFrame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        mainFrame.setSize(800, 600);

        JPanel contentPanel = new JPanel(null);
        setupDropTarget(contentPanel);

        String[] components = {"Button", "Label", /* Add more component names here */};
        JList<String> componentList = new JList<>(components);
        componentList.setSelectionMode(ListSelectionModel.SINGLE_SELECTION);
        componentList.setDragEnabled(true);

        JScrollPane listScrollPane = new JScrollPane(componentList);
        mainFrame.add(listScrollPane, BorderLayout.WEST);
        mainFrame.add(contentPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        mainFrame.setVisible(true);
    }

    private static void setupDropTarget(JPanel panel) {
        panel.setDropTarget(new DropTarget(panel, DnDConstants.ACTION_COPY, new DropTargetAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void drop(DropTargetDropEvent event) {
                event.acceptDrop(DnDConstants.ACTION_COPY);
                Transferable transferable = event.getTransferable();
                try {
                    String data = (String) transferable.getTransferData(DataFlavor.stringFlavor);
                    DraggablePanel componentPanel = ComponentFactory.createSampleComponent(data);
                    Point dropPoint = event.getLocation();
                    componentPanel.setLocation(dropPoint);
                    panel.add(componentPanel);
                    panel.repaint();
                } catch (Exception e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                }
            }
        }, true, null));
    }
}
```

This example application provides a simple JFrame with a JList on the left, which contains the 10 example components (in this case, just "Button" and "Label"). The user can drag a component from the JList and drop it onto the content panel, which will add the draggable component to the panel.

You can easily extend the list of component types in the `ComponentFactory` class and in the `components` array in the `DragAndDropGUI` class.

Please note that this is a basic example, and there's room for improvement and enhancements. For example, you may want to store the component's state, allow the user to add more than one of each type, or improve the appearance of drag-and-drop interactions.

In this example, we'll use JAXB (Java Architecture for XML Binding) to write and read Employee objects using XML. JAXB is included in JDK by default (until JDK 11) and allows you to easily manage XML serialization and deserialization.

1. First, create the `Employee` class and add JAXB annotations:

```java
import javax.xml.bind.annotation.XmlAccessType;
import javax.xml.bind.annotation.XmlAccessorType;
import javax.xml.bind.annotation.XmlElement;
import javax.xml.bind.annotation.XmlRootElement;

@XmlRootElement(name = "employee")
@XmlAccessorType(XmlAccessType.FIELD)
public class Employee {

    @XmlElement(name = "id")
    private Long id;

    @XmlElement(name = "name")
    private String name;

    @XmlElement(name = "position")
    private String position;

    @XmlElement(name = "email")
    private String email;

    // constructors, getters, and setters
}
```

2. Add JAXB and an XML library to your project. If you are using Maven, add the following dependencies to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>javax.xml.bind</groupId>
        <artifactId>jaxb-api</artifactId>
        <version>2.3.1</version>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.glassfish.jaxb</groupId>
        <artifactId>jaxb-runtime</artifactId>
        <version>2.3.3</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

3. Create a `JAXBUtil` class to handle XML serialization and deserialization:

```java
import javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext;
import javax.xml.bind.JAXBException;
import javax.xml.bind.Marshaller;
import javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller;
import java.io.StringReader;
import java.io.StringWriter;

public class JAXBUtil {

    public static String toXml(Object object) throws JAXBException {
        StringWriter stringWriter = new StringWriter();
        JAXBContext jaxbContext = JAXBContext.newInstance(object.getClass());
        Marshaller jaxbMarshaller = jaxbContext.createMarshaller();
        jaxbMarshaller.setProperty(Marshaller.JAXB_FORMATTED_OUTPUT, true);
        jaxbMarshaller.marshal(object, stringWriter);
        return stringWriter.toString();
    }

    public static <T> T fromXml(String xmlString, Class<T> valueType) throws JAXBException {
        JAXBContext jaxbContext = JAXBContext.newInstance(valueType);
        Unmarshaller jaxbUnmarshaller = jaxbContext.createUnmarshaller();
        return (T) jaxbUnmarshaller.unmarshal(new StringReader(xmlString));
    }
}
```

4. Use `JAXBUtil` to convert Employee objects to XML and vice versa:

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee employee = new Employee(1L, "John Doe", "Software Engineer", "john.doe@example.com");

        String xmlString;
        try {
            xmlString = JAXBUtil.toXml(employee);
            System.out.println("Employee object serialized to XML:");
            System.out.println(xmlString);
        } catch (JAXBException e) {
            System.err.println("Error serializing Employee object");
            e.printStackTrace();
            return;
        }

        Employee deserializedEmployee;
        try {
            deserializedEmployee = JAXBUtil.fromXml(xmlString, Employee.class);
            System.out.println("Employee object deserialized from XML:");
            System.out.println(deserializedEmployee.getName());
        } catch (JAXBException e) {
            System.err.println("Error deserializing Employee object");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

When you run the `Main` class example, it will create an Employee object, serialize it to an XML string, print the XML, then deserialize an Employee object from the XML string and print the employee's name.

In this example, we will use the Apache PDFBox library to parse a PDF file, extract text, and count the occurrences of each word using a HashMap.

1. First, add the Apache PDFBox dependency to your project. If you are using Maven, add the following dependency to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.apache.pdfbox</groupId>
        <artifactId>pdfbox</artifactId>
        <version>2.0.24</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

2. Create a utility class called `PDFParser` to extract text from the PDF file:

```java
import org.apache.pdfbox.pdmodel.PDDocument;
import org.apache.pdfbox.text.PDFTextStripper;

import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class PDFParser {

    public static String getTextFromFile(String filePath) throws IOException {
        PDDocument document = PDDocument.load(new File(filePath));
        PDFTextStripper pdfStripper = new PDFTextStripper();

        String text = pdfStripper.getText(document);

        document.close();

        return text;
    }
}
```

3. Create the `Main` class to read a PDF file, parse its content to ASCII, and count words occurrences using a HashMap:

```java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class Main {

    public static Map<Integer, String> countWords(String text) {
        String[] words = text.split("\\W+");
        Map<Integer, String> wordOccurrences = new HashMap<>();

        for (String word : words) {
            if (word.isEmpty()) {
                continue;
            }
            wordOccurrences.putIfAbsent(word.length(), "");
            wordOccurrences.put(word.length(), wordOccurrences.get(word.length()) + " " + (word.toLowerCase()));
        }

        return wordOccurrences;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String filePath = "path/to/your/pdf-file.pdf";
        String text;

        try {
            text = PDFParser.getTextFromFile(filePath);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.err.println("Error reading PDF file");
            e.printStackTrace();
            return;
        }

        Map<Integer, String> wordOccurrences = countWords(text);

        System.out.println("Occurrences of each word:");
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : wordOccurrences.entrySet()) {
            System.out.println("Words of length " + entry.getKey() + ": " + entry.getValue());
        }
    }
}
```

Replace the `path/to/your/pdf-file.pdf` with the path to a PDF file you want to process.

When you run the `Main` class, it will parse the specified PDF file, extract text, and count the occurrences of words by counting their length. The result will be stored in a `HashMap` with word length as key and words as values, then printed to the console.

Note: The `countWords` method works under the assumption that words are separated by non-word characters (spaces, punctuation, etc.). This method may not work correctly for languages that do not use spaces between words. Additionally, you might want to further enhance the counting mechanism if needed.

In this example, we'll use H2 Database to execute the 10 most used SQL commands from within a Java application. We will use `java.sql` package to interact with the database.

1. First, add the H2 Dependency to your project. If you're using Maven, add the following dependency to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>
        <artifactId>h2</artifactId>
        <version>1.4.200</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

2. Create a utility class called `DatabaseUtil` for running SQL commands:

```java
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.ResultSet;
import java.sql.SQLException;
import java.sql.Statement;

public class DatabaseUtil {

    private static final String CONNECTION_URL = "jdbc:h2:mem:test;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1";

    public static Connection connect() throws SQLException {
        return DriverManager.getConnection(CONNECTION_URL);
    }
}
```

3. Create the `Main` class with examples of the 10 most used SQL commands:

```java
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.ResultSet;
import java.sql.SQLException;
import java.sql.Statement;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try (Connection connection = DatabaseUtil.connect()) {

            // 1. CREATE TABLE
            String createTableCommand = "CREATE TABLE employee (" +
                    "id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY," +
                    "name VARCHAR(255)," +
                    "position VARCHAR(255))";
            executeUpdate(connection, createTableCommand);

            // 2. INSERT
            String insertCommand = "INSERT INTO employee (name, position) VALUES ('John Doe', 'Software Engineer')";
            executeUpdate(connection, insertCommand);

            // 3. SELECT
            String selectCommand = "SELECT * FROM employee";
            ResultSet resultSet = executeQuery(connection, selectCommand);

            System.out.println("Employee records:");
            while (resultSet.next()) {
                System.out.printf("%d, %s, %s%n", resultSet.getInt("id"), resultSet.getString("name"),
                        resultSet.getString("position"));
            }

            // 4. UPDATE
            String updateCommand = "UPDATE employee SET position = 'Senior Software Engineer' WHERE id = 1";
            executeUpdate(connection, updateCommand);

            // 5. DELETE
            String deleteCommand = "DELETE FROM employee WHERE id = 1";
            executeUpdate(connection, deleteCommand);

            // 6. ALTER TABLE (Add new column)
            String alterTableCommand = "ALTER TABLE employee ADD COLUMN email VARCHAR(255)";
            executeUpdate(connection, alterTableCommand);

            // 7. DROP TABLE
            String dropTableCommand = "DROP TABLE employee";
            executeUpdate(connection, dropTableCommand);

            // Note: The following three commands are H2-specific and might not be applicable to other databases.

            // 8. CREATE ALIAS (functions)
            String createAliasCommand = "CREATE ALIAS MY_CONCAT FOR \"org.h2.api.AggregateFunction$concat\";";
            executeUpdate(connection, createAliasCommand);

            // 9. CREATE TRIGGER
            createTableCommand = "CREATE TABLE test_trigger(id INT PRIMARY KEY, value INT);";
            executeUpdate(connection, createTableCommand);
            String createTriggerCommand = "CREATE TRIGGER my_trigger before INSERT ON test_trigger CALL \"org.h2.samples.Trigger\";";
            executeUpdate(connection, createTriggerCommand);

            // 10. CREATE SEQUENCE
            String createSequenceCommand = "CREATE SEQUENCE test_sequence;";
            executeUpdate(connection, createSequenceCommand);

            // 10. SELECT NEXT VALUE from SEQUENCE
            String getNextValueFromSequenceCommand = "SELECT NEXT VALUE FOR test_sequence";
            resultSet = executeQuery(connection, getNextValueFromSequenceCommand);
            if (resultSet.next()) {
                System.out.printf("Next value for test_sequence: %d%n", resultSet.getInt(1));
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            System.err.println("Error executing SQL commands");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    private static void executeUpdate(Connection connection, String command) throws SQLException {
        Statement statement = connection.createStatement();
        statement.executeUpdate(command);
    }

    private static ResultSet executeQuery(Connection connection, String command) throws SQLException {
        Statement statement = connection.createStatement();
        return statement.executeQuery(command);
    }
}
```

In the `Main` class, we execute 10 most used SQL commands:

1. CREATE TABLE
2. INSERT
3. SELECT
4. UPDATE
5. DELETE
6. ALTER TABLE (for adding new columns)
7. DROP TABLE
8. CREATE ALIAS (H2-specific, for creating a function alias)
9. CREATE TRIGGER (H2-specific)
10. CREATE SEQUENCE/SELECT NEXT VALUE FOR (H2-specific, creating and using sequences)

Keep in mind that the last three SQL commands in this example are H2-specific and might not work directly with other databases.

When running the `Main` class, it will connect to the in-memory H2 database and execute SQL commands, interacting with the database.

In this example, we'll use an open-source Look-and-Feel called FlatLaf to create a custom-themed Java Swing application.

1. First, add the FlatLaf dependency to your project. If you're using Maven, add the following dependency to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.formdev</groupId>
        <artifactId>flatlaf</artifactId>
        <version>1.6</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

2. Create a simple application with a `JFrame` that uses the FlatLaf Look-and-Feel:

```java
import com.formdev.flatlaf.FlatDarkLaf;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JButton;
import javax.swing.JPanel;
import javax.swing.UIManager;
import javax.swing.UnsupportedLookAndFeelException;

public class CustomLookAndFeelExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            UIManager.setLookAndFeel(new FlatDarkLaf());
        } catch (UnsupportedLookAndFeelException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Custom Look and Feel");
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setSize(400, 300);

        JPanel contentPanel = new JPanel();
        JButton button = new JButton("A Button with Custom Look and Feel");

        contentPanel.add(button);
        frame.add(contentPanel);

        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

In this example, we set the Look-and-Feel of the application to `FlatDarkLaf()`, which provides a custom dark theme. The example creates a simple `JFrame` with a button that applies the custom theme.

To switch to another theme, you can use alternatives such as `FlatLightLaf`, `FlatIntelliJLaf`, or `FlatDarculaLaf` by changing the `UIManager.setLookAndFeel()` argument.

You can also create your own theme based on the FlatLaf framework by extending their classes and customizing the colors and configurations. For more information on FlatLaf, check out their GitHub repository: https://github.com/JFormDesigner/FlatLaf
